healthy1: Where there is a partnership of all aspects of the relationship, so between you you have the capacity to support each other as the other needs it. This could be one paying bills from a joint account because the other is awful at it, while the other does the DIY because the other is awful at that. Taking time to make each other feel valid despite any flaws, and taking the time to check in that the other person is OK both emotionally and mentally, and then making sure to take action when a decline is seen. This takes a lot of listening and organisation, but if either party feels invalid in their thoughts or reasons then the opposite will happen and the relationship will suffer.
healthy2: You have to have trust in the other person that they are not going to perform actions you disagree with (so discussions at length to ensure both parties know the others thresholds for acceptable behaviour are needed). Obviously we are all humans, and humans lie, however if you have had the discussion on how you want to be treated and cared for, and you know how they do, and have come to an agreement between you, then the relationship should remain healthy. If negative indicators appear (e.g. cheating, being rude or disrespectful to your other family members, not supporting your partner) then you know it is not healthy and can take the appropriate action. It should be easy to be with the other person because you work as a team. If it starts to feel like work then something is wrong, so just be more observant to figure out what is wrong and if it is fixable or not. Healthy relationships are about 60% happiness (i.e. do you feel happy?) and 40% mind-thoughtfulness (did you support your partner by earning money for rent, organising the kids, remembering and being there for their birthday)
healthy3: Trust first, with an ounce of skepticism to question 'is this right?'. Discuss your relationship regularly so you both know you are on the same page and are moving at the same speed so both parties are comfortable and enjoy the relationship (rather than feeling scared because it's too fast/ too slow/ too unknown). Celebrate the other person just because they are them - bring them a token (be it a hand written post it note in their work lunch, or a text just to say how amazing they are - it doesn't have to cost money). Be aware that things can go wrong so be present to discuss an adjustments you need to make together, and above all be kind, always.
unhealthy: Thresholds you and your partner (or other party) had discussed are breached in some manner. You arrange a family dinner and they don't show up and are rude about it after, or they forget your birthday and don't make up for missing it. People are hurt and angered more by little things, so be vigilant for these, and be organised. If the organisation is gone, the relationship will follow the same downward spiral.

healthy1: I define a healthy relationship as one where both people view each other as equals, and as equally deserving of respect. A healthy relationship is one where both people feel free to come to the other with any problems they might have (especially within the relationship, but other problems as well) and trust that their partner will listen to them and genuinely try to understand the problem, and help/fix it if necessary/appropriate.
healthy2: It can be hard to know if it's unhealthy, but I think one big factor is how the relationship makes you feel, or how being with your partner makes you feel. It doesn't always have to be happy or positive feelings (because arguments and disagreements can be a part of a healthy relationship as well), but I think that feelings of dread, panic, anxiety, etc. are not typically present in a healthy relationship. If a person dreads when their partner comes home from work, or dreads going on a vacation together, or things like that, then I think that that can be a sign that there's a serious problem.
healthy3: I think the most important thing in a healthy relationship is respect for the other person. Everything else is built on a foundation of respect. Respect for them as a human being, respect for their autonomy, respect for their decisions, respect for their privacy, respect for their other relationships. In addition to that, I think that understanding and empathy are also very important, because those can help you understand your partner's behaviors or perspectives.
unhealthy: I kind of answered this before, but -- overwhelming negative feelings in relation to the relationship. A healthy relationship doesn't need to always be happy, positive, fun, etc., but the positives should certainly outweigh the negatives, or else why be together? So, feeling primarily negatively about the relationship, your partner, your future together, etc. is a sign that a relationship is not healthy.
